    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Actiones Consulum, aut Decemuirûm, aut Tribunoru[m] militum consulari potestate, aut alioru[m] magistratuu[m], 
                        pra[e]terq[uam] Dictatorum, minus meruerunt ponderis, aut examinis politici, quàm actiones Regum. Veruntamen hîc etiam Romana Prudentia, 
                        et fortitudo; ciuilis temperantia, et iustitia. Vtinam tam priuatim integra, quàm publicè magnifica.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The actions of the Consuls, Decemviri, Military Tribunes with consular authority or other magistrates, except Dictators, 
                deserve less consideration, or political scrutiny than the deeds of Kings. Still in this area there is also Roman Sagacity and Strength, 
                civic restraint and justice. If only these [actions] were as irreproachable privately as they were excellent publicly.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>De primis apud Rom. consulibus, quoru[m] alter alterum patria pepulit; moxq[ue] Roma[e] post atrocissima parricidia, à vulnerato hoste 
                        vulneratus interijt. Augustinus l. 3. c. 16. de Ciuitate Dei. Vt etiam idem c. 17. post initia consularis imperij, quibus malis vexata fuerit Rom. 
                        Respublica; Dijs non opitulantibus, quos colebat. Duo literata, valdeq[ue] notabilia capita acutissimi Doctoris. Nec spernendi Viuis eruditi 
                        Commentarij. Cuius illud memorabile: Homines de plebe, suis actionib[us] pra[e]tendebant, se iura populi, et commune[m] Libertatem defendere: 
                        patritij contra niti, et multum de commodis vulgi detrahere, vt id sibi apponerent; illo pra[e]textu, quòd dignitatem Senatus tuerentur 
                       , quam esse amplissimam è Repub. foret. Sed re vera pro sua potentia quisq[ue] certare. Quod toties infra occurrens, 
                        semel hîc videbatur obseruandum.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Augustine"/>
                    <person name="Juan Luis Vives"/>
                    <book title="De Civitate Dei"/>
                    <book title="Commentarii"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Of the first Roman consuls, one of whom expelled the other, and soon afterwards perished by a wound inflicted by a wounded enemy, after the most atrocious parricide: Augustine, bk. 3, c. 16 of the City of God. 
                As also in the same book, c. 17: Of the ills by which the Roman commonwealth was vexed after the inauguration of the consulate, while no help was offered 
                by the gods whom the Romans worshipped. Two erudite and highly significant chapters of the extremely perceptive Doctor. 
                One should not disregard Vives' learned Commentary. From which comes this remarkable passage: Men from the common people pretended with 
                their actions to defend the rights of the people and joint liberty; the patricians conversely exerted themselves to take away much from the 
                people’s benefits in order to claim it for themselves, under the pretext that they were guarding the dignity of the Senate, which had to be 
                greatest in the Repubic. But in reality everyone was fighting for his own power. As this happens so often below, it seemed it should be noted here once.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Rex sacrificulus, titularis rex. Species sine re, ad pascendum oculos regiorum fautorum. 
                        Elenchus signoru[m]: sa[e]pe ualdè politicus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The 'rex sacrificulus' [the king of sacrifices] was a king in name only. The appearance without the substance, for royal supporters to feast their eyes on. 
                The investigation of signs was often very political.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Latet anguis in herba.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>A snake hides in the grass.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>Practica Regia, pro recuperando Regno; primò Priuata, et sophistica; deinde publica, et bellica. Astuta, et valida, ni fuisset 
                        Brutus vir: et absolutus Artifex vtenda[e] occasionis. Nunc animis opus, Ænea: nunc pectore firmo.
                        Quicquid erant hi, aut illi Romani, seu publica[e], seu priuata[e] persona[e], qui erant pla[e]runq[ue], in sua quisq[ue] functione, enixe prudentes, 
                        atq[ue] strenui: certè Liuius, semper est Lectu, animaduersu[que] dignissimus. Vt eccè à pagina in paginam, vbi vbi [sic] voles. 
                        Quod ego de perpaucis dixerim simul eloquentissimis, simul sapientissimis auctoribus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Lucius Junius Brutus"/>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                    <X-ref book_title="Aeneid" language="LA" person="Virgil" text="Nunc animis opus, Ænea: nunc pectore firmo"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Royal actions to regain the rule: first private and cunning, then public and military. Shrewd and effective [actions], if Brutus had not been a man, 
                and a perfect master in seizing the opportunity. “Now Aeneas, courage is needed, now a resolute mind.”
                Whoever these or other Romans were, public or private characters, who were generally strenuously prudent and vigorous in their respective capacities, 
                Livy is surely always superbly worth reading and attending to. As you can see page after page, wherever you want. And I would say this only about very 
                few authors, who are both extremely eloquent and extremely wise.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
